<subSubSection id="C35465071C01756DFF2F95B0999FC753" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BF1368C1C01756DFF2F95B0999FC753" blockId="5.[151,1437,152,971]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C01756DFF2F95B09C52C6A3" bold="true" box="[151,274,152,179]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C01756DFEA195B19CF4C6A3" authorityName="Swainson (Stripey" authorityYear="1839" box="[281,436,153,179]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Microcanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C01756DFEA195B19CF4C6A3" box="[281,436,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Microcanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is readily distinguished from all other microcanthid genera in having the following combination of characters: dorsal fin with XI spines and 15–17 (usually 16) segmented rays; anal fin with III spines and 13–15 (usually 14) segmented rays; pectoral fin with 15–17 (usually 16) rays; scales ctenoid, with ctenial bases present; lateral line scales partially or heavily obscured by adjacent scales; and body pale in preservation with five horizontal dark stripes reaching the posterior edges of dorsal and anal fins, and base of caudal fin.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35465071C01756EFF7F94649FA1C7BF" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="47" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BF1368C1C01756DFF7F94649808C497" blockId="5.[151,1437,152,971]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C01756DFF7F94649C19C777" bold="true" box="[199,345,332,359]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Description.</emphasis>
Dorsal-fin rays XI,15–17, all segmented rays branched except anteriormost; soft dorsal fin extensively covered in scales, scales reaching almost to distal edge of fin; anal-fin rays III,13–15, all segmented rays branched; basal portion of dorsal and anal fins with scale sheaths; pectoral-fin rays 14–17, all rays branched except for uppermost; dorsal and anal fin spines stiff and pungent; second anal-fin spine blade-like; base of pectoral fin covered in numerous small scales, scales reaching just beyond base of fin rays; inner pelvic-fin ray not attached to body by membrane; pelvic-fin rays I,5, all segmented rays branched; upper procurrent caudal-fin rays 8–9; lower procurrent caudal-fin rays 7–9; principal caudal-fin rays 9 + 8 (8 + 7 branched); total caudal-fin rays 32–35; lateral line complete; tubed scales irregularly obscured by overlapping scales; scales ctenoid with ctenial bases; diagonal rows of scales in lateral series 48–59; circumpeduncular scales 26–30; gill rakers 16–18; branchiostegals 7.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF1368C1C01756DFF7F97B9980AC5DB" blockId="5.[151,1437,152,971]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">
Vertebrae 10 + 15; supraneurals 3; predorsal formula 0/0+0/2/1+1; trisegmental pterygiophores associated with segmented rays of the dorsal (except the anteriormost 3–5 bisegmental) and anal fins (except the anteriormost 3–4 bisegmental); terminal rays in dorsal and anal fins with well-developed stays; ribs present on vertebrae 3 through 10; epineurals present on vertebrae 1 through 10–12 (usually 11); parhypural and hypurals 1–5 autogenous; welldeveloped hypurapophysis on parhypural; epurals 3, anteriormost largest; two uroneurals; uppermost procurrent ray on ventral part of caudal fin with procurrent spur, the ray immediately below foreshortened (
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF4B7D1C01756DFB20966D9878C54F" author="Johnson, G. D." box="[1176,1336,836,863]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" pagination="1 - 23" refId="ref11517" refString="Johnson, G. D. (1975) The procurrent spur: an undescribed perciform caudal character and its phylogenetic implications. Occasional Papers of the California Academy of Sciences, 121, 1 - 23." type="journal article" year="1975">Johnson 1975</bibRefCitation>
); haemal spines on preural centrum 2 and 3 autogenous (
<figureCitation id="13752A091C01756DFD1196419E48C593" box="[681,776,873,899]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1973,1998]" captionTargetBox="[166,1422,993,1948]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[166,1422,990,1950]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 1. X-radiograph of Microcanthus strigatus, KPM-NI 24269, 73.8 mm SL, Yakushima Island, Japan. Radiograph by A. Hay." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3904878" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3904878/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Figure 1</figureCitation>
); interarcual cartilage present between uncinate process of epibranchial 1 and pharyngobranchial 2; no toothplates on epibranchial 2 or 3; well-developed suborbital shelf on third infraorbital; posttemporal and preopercle finely serrate; laterosensory canal present in supracleithrum.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF3166041C01756DFF2F929D9DA6C1E2" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3904878" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3904878" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3904878/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" startId="5.[151,250,1973,1998]" targetBox="[166,1422,993,1948]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph id="8BF1368C1C01756DFF2F929D9DA6C1E2" blockId="5.[151,1436,1973,2034]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C01756DFF2F929D9C54C1DE" bold="true" box="[151,276,1973,1998]" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">FIGURE 1.</emphasis>
X-radiograph of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C01756DFE7F929D9FF3C1DD" baseAuthorityName="Cuvier in Cuvier &amp; Valenciennes" baseAuthorityYear="1831" box="[455,691,1973,1997]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Microcanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="strigatus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C01756DFE7F929D9FF3C1DD" box="[455,691,1973,1997]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="46">Microcanthus strigatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, KPM-NI 24269, 73.8 mm SL, Yakushima Island, Japan. Radiograph by A. Hay.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BF1368C1C02756EFF7F95B19FA1C7BF" blockId="6.[151,1437,152,935]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Body laterally compressed, moderately tall in lateral view, dorsal-fin origin to pelvic-fin origin 51.9– 59.8% SL; head small 28.1–36.6% SL; snout acute, 7.8–11.0% SL; head profile steeply sloping, slightly concave; eye large, 11.0–14.6% SL; mouth terminal, horizontal to slightly oblique; distal portion of maxilla partly covered by lachrymal, barely reaching anterior edge of orbit; preopercle serrated; lower jaw projecting slightly; jaws with numerous rows of small, setiform teeth anteriorly; preorbital region naked; scales large, ctenoid with ctenial bases, covering the body from postorbital region of operculum and the cheek, posteriorly to base of caudal fin; interorbital region naked, 8.3–11.4% SL in width; pelvic fin free, not bound to body by a membrane, situated well behind vertical through pectoral-fin base; caudal fin emarginate.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35465071C02756EFF7F94919965C7E7" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BF1368C1C02756EFF7F94919965C7E7" blockId="6.[151,1437,152,935]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFF7F94919C0EC7C3" bold="true" box="[199,334,441,467]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Etymology.</emphasis>
The generic epithet 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFD8994919F8CC7C3" authorityName="Swainson (Stripey" authorityYear="1839" box="[561,716,441,467]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Microcanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFD8994919F8CC7C3" box="[561,716,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Microcanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a combination of the Greek “mikros” for small, and “akantha” for thorn, alluding to the minute crenulations on the preopercle (
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF4B7D1C02756EFCDE94F59958C7E7" author="Swainson, W." box="[870,1048,477,503]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" refId="ref13157" refString="Swainson, W. (1839) On the Natural History and Classification of Fishes, Amphibians, &amp; Reptiles, or Monocardian animals. Vol. 2. Spottiswoode &amp; Co., London, 427 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 62140" type="book" year="1839">Swainson 1839</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35465071C02756EFF7F97299FCBC5B7" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BF1368C1C02756EFF7F97299906C4BB" blockId="6.[151,1437,152,935]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFF7F97299C7BC40B" bold="true" box="[199,315,513,539]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Remarks.</emphasis>
The various genera of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFDF797299FBFC40B" box="[591,767,513,539]" family="Microcanthidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Microcanthidae</taxonomicName>
are readily separated on the basis of dorsal- and anal-fin counts, scale morphology, body shape, and general coloration. 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFCE4970D9EF2C42F" authorityName="Thominot" authorityYear="1881" box="[860,946,549,575]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Tilodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFCE4970D9EF2C42F" box="[860,946,549,575]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Tilodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFC51970E9911C42F" authorityName="Waite" authorityYear="1905" box="[1001,1105,550,575]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Neatypus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFC51970E9911C42F" box="[1001,1105,550,575]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Neatypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be separated from 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFAE0970D9D9FC473" authorityName="Gunther" authorityYear="1862" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Atypichthys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFAE0970D9D9FC473" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Atypichthys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFEA197619CF4C473" authorityName="Swainson (Stripey" authorityYear="1839" box="[281,436,585,611]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Microcanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFEA197619CF4C473" box="[281,436,585,611]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Microcanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having ten dorsal fin spines (versus 
<quantity id="4CB69B691C02756EFCC097619EF2C473" box="[888,946,585,611]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.794" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" unit="in" value="11.0">11 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFC029761997DC473" authorityName="Gunther" authorityYear="1862" box="[954,1085,585,611]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Atypichthys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFC029761997DC473" box="[954,1085,585,611]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Atypichthys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFBCF97619851C473" authorityName="Swainson (Stripey" authorityYear="1839" box="[1143,1297,585,611]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Microcanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFBCF97619851C473" box="[1143,1297,585,611]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Microcanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and higher dorsal-and anal-fin ray counts. The four genera can be separated further on the basis of colour patterns, in having either vertical or oblique bars versus horizontal or near-horizontal stripes (
<figureCitation id="13752A091C02756EFC6E97B99979C4BB" box="[982,1081,657,683]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1845,1870]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,957,1820]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[154,1433,957,1820]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 2. Genera of Microcanthidae. Tilodon and Neatypus are monotypic. A) Tilodon sexfasciatus, in situ photograph from Blairgowrie, Victoria, Australia; B) Neatypus obliquus, in situ photograph from Bunbury, Western Australia; C) Microcanthus joyceae, in situ photograph from Magic Point, Maroubra, New South Wales, Australia; and D) Atypichthys strigatus, in situ photograph from Henry Head, Botany Bay, New South Wales, Australia. Photographs by S. Schulz (A), C. Mark (B), and E. Schlogl (C &amp; D)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3904880" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3904880/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Figure 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF1368C1C02756EFF7F979D9FCBC5B7" blockId="6.[151,1437,152,935]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
The lateral-line scales of at least 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFD86979D9F98C4DF" authorityName="Swainson (Stripey" authorityYear="1839" box="[574,728,693,719]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Microcanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFD86979D9F98C4DF" box="[574,728,693,719]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Microcanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFD50979D9E2BC4DF" authorityName="Gunther" authorityYear="1862" box="[744,875,693,719]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Atypichthys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFD50979D9E2BC4DF" box="[744,875,693,719]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Atypichthys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFC1B979D9EB9C4DF" authorityName="Thominot" authorityYear="1881" box="[931,1017,693,719]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Tilodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFC1B979D9EB9C4DF" box="[931,1017,693,719]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Tilodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are heavily obscured by overlapping adjacent scales (
<figureCitation id="13752A091C02756EFEF497F19CEDC4E3" box="[332,429,729,755]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1241,1266]" captionTargetBox="[161,1426,181,1216]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[161,1426,181,1216]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Lateral-line scales of: A) Scorpis lineolatus (Scorpididae), AMS I.48993-001, 55.3 mm SL; B) Microcanthus joyceae (Microcanthidae), AMS I.48994-001, 64.2 mm SL; C) Atypichthys strigatus (Microcanthidae), AMS I.48992-001, 93.9 mm SL. Drawings on right show portion of lateral line and adjacent scales. Lateral-line scales are show in dark grey; scale bars indicate 2 mm. Photographs by Y.K. Tea; drawings by A.C. Gill." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3904882" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3904882/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Figure 3</figureCitation>
). This appears to be an ontogenetic character, as juveniles have mostly unobscured lateralline scales, but these become increasingly obscured in larger specimens. This character is not found in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFA8C97D698DCC507" authorityName="Waite" authorityYear="1905" box="[1332,1436,766,791]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Neatypus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFA8C97D698DCC507" box="[1332,1436,766,791]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Neatypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(checked for and examined in 
<typeStatus id="54F5882E1C02756EFE5D96099F7CC52B" box="[485,572,801,827]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">syntype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFDE7960A9E69C52B" authority="Waite" authorityName="Waite" authorityYear="1905" box="[607,809,801,827]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Neatypus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="obliquus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFDE7960A9F9FC52B" box="[607,735,801,827]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">N. obliquus</emphasis>
Waite
</taxonomicName>
; AMS I.7034). Whether it is a synapomorphy supporting a relationship between 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFE21966D9F73C54F" authorityName="Swainson (Stripey" authorityYear="1839" box="[409,563,837,863]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Microcanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFE21966D9F73C54F" box="[409,563,837,863]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Microcanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFDF9966D9F84C54F" authorityName="Gunther" authorityYear="1862" box="[577,708,837,863]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Atypichthys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFDF9966D9F84C54F" box="[577,708,837,863]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Atypichthys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFD42966D9E10C54F" authorityName="Thominot" authorityYear="1881" box="[762,848,837,863]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Tilodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFD42966D9E10C54F" box="[762,848,837,863]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Tilodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
requires more investigation. We tentatively consider 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFF2F96419F40C594" authority="Kaup (1863)" authorityName="Kaup" authorityYear="1863" box="[151,512,873,900]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Helotosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="servus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFF2F96419C2CC593" box="[151,364,873,899]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Helotosoma servus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF4B7D1C02756EFEC996419F40C594" author="Kaup, J. J." box="[369,512,873,900]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" pagination="161 - 162" refId="ref11999" refString="Kaup, J. J. (1863) Uber einige japanische Fische. Nederlandsch Tijdschrift voor de Dierkunde, 1, 161 - 162." type="journal article" year="1863">Kaup (1863)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, type species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFD0C96419E90C594" authority="Kaup (1863)" authorityName="Kaup" authorityYear="1863" box="[692,976,873,900]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Helotosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFD0C96419E7BC593" box="[692,827,873,899]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Helotosoma</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF4B7D1C02756EFCF996419E90C594" author="Kaup, J. J." box="[833,976,873,900]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" pagination="161 - 162" refId="ref11999" refString="Kaup, J. J. (1863) Uber einige japanische Fische. Nederlandsch Tijdschrift voor de Dierkunde, 1, 161 - 162." type="journal article" year="1863">Kaup (1863)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFB2B964198D5C593" baseAuthorityName="Cuvier in Cuvier &amp; Valenciennes" baseAuthorityYear="1831" box="[1171,1429,873,899]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Microcanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="strigatus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFB2B964198D5C593" box="[1171,1429,873,899]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Microcanthus strigatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. See Remarks for 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D0F1C02756EFEE196A69CA0C5B7" baseAuthorityName="Cuvier in Cuvier &amp; Valenciennes" baseAuthorityYear="1831" box="[345,480,910,935]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Kyphosidae" genus="Microcanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="strigatus">
<emphasis id="B93AEA9E1C02756EFEE196A69CA0C5B7" box="[345,480,910,935]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">M. strigatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for discussion.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
